📝 C. Specialty String — Notes (CP Ready)
🧠 Problem Summary

Given a string s

You can remove two equal characters s[i] == s[j] if:

i < j

All characters between them are already *

👉 After removal → both become *
👉 Goal → make entire string *

🔥 Key Observation

You can only remove characters if they are effectively adjacent

Because:

Between them must be all *

So after removals → characters become adjacent

💡 Core Idea

👉 This reduces to:

Can we repeatedly remove adjacent equal characters until string becomes empty?

🧩 Pattern Recognition

This is similar to:

Valid Parentheses

Remove Adjacent Duplicates

Stack-based cancellation problems

⚙️ Approach (Stack)
Algorithm:

Create empty stack

Traverse string:

If stack not empty AND top == current → pop()

Else → push()

At end:

Empty stack → YES

Otherwise → NO

💻 Python Code
import sys
input = sys.stdin.readline

t = int(input())
for _ in range(t):
    n = int(input())
    s = input().strip()
    
    stack = []
    
    for c in s:
        if stack and stack[-1] == c:
            stack.pop()
        else:
            stack.append(c)
    
    print("YES" if not stack else "NO")
⚡ Complexity

Time: O(n)

Space: O(n)

🔍 Example
Input:
abba
Process:
a → push → [a]
b → push → [a, b]
b → match → pop → [a]
a → match → pop → []

👉 Result: YES

❌ Common Mistakes
1. Only checking frequency

Even count ≠ always valid

Order matters ❗

2. Not understanding condition

sk = * for all i < k < j

👉 Means:

No characters between → effectively adjacent

3. Forgetting .strip()

Can include \n → breaks logic

🚀 Key Takeaways

Convert complex condition → adjacency problem

Stack = best tool for pair removal problems

Always simplify problem statement

